1
00:00:02,072 --> 00:00:07,963
Tonight I want to look at the way Meta shades in tone when we come across difficulties.

2
00:00:09,305 --> 00:00:12,089
Meta itself remains intact.

3
00:00:12,109 --> 00:00:15,115
Our basis is wishing ourselves and others well.

4
00:00:16,338 --> 00:00:22,849
But the goodwill is expressed in compassionate terms with sensitivity to the particular situation.

5
00:00:23,977 --> 00:00:30,751
Compassion is sometimes described as the trembling of the enlightened heart in response to the suffering of the world.

6
00:00:31,472 --> 00:00:37,585
There is deep sympathy with the suffering being and the wish that their suffering may come to an end.

7
00:00:38,527 --> 00:00:40,871
But there is no anxiety about the situation.

8
00:00:41,792 --> 00:00:45,039
This can be very difficult for us to understand.

9
00:00:45,020 --> 00:00:57,731
the enlightened being is in touch with a level of peace that is untouched by the suffering and can sustain a calm tenderness even when the heart is breaking or the body is being torn apart.

10
00:00:59,694 --> 00:01:03,518
Within the context of peace and tenderness anything can be born.

11
00:01:04,498 --> 00:01:12,867
This is what Julian of Norwich learned when in revulsion at the sufferings of the world she heard the words all shall be well

12
00:01:13,420 --> 00:01:19,870
All shall be well and all manner of things shall be well.

13
00:01:19,890 --> 00:01:24,677
Compassion is the manifestation of wisdom in the face of suffering.

14
00:01:24,697 --> 00:01:33,150
It allows the suffering to elicit a response of tenderness and care without any hint of anxiety or aversion.

15
00:01:34,700 --> 00:01:42,793
Sustained by compassion, the enlightened person does not get in any way flustered by the situation and can respond appropriately.

16
00:01:43,453 --> 00:01:48,182
For example, caring for an injured being, finding words to comfort.

17
00:01:49,364 --> 00:02:01,483
The Vinaya, the book of monastic discipline, includes a story of the Buddha and Ananda coming across a monk who had acute dysentery and was lying in his soiled robes.

18
00:02:01,817 --> 00:02:04,561
You can imagine the sight and the stench.

19
00:02:05,804 --> 00:02:08,927
The Buddha and Ananda cleaned the monk and his robes.

20
00:02:09,609 --> 00:02:20,104
Afterwards, the Buddha addressed the Sikh monks' fellows, clarifying that it was their duty to look after one another in case of illness.

21
00:02:21,186 --> 00:02:26,073
Monks, he said, if you don't tend to one another, who then will tend to you?

22
00:02:26,112 --> 00:02:29,698
Whoever would tend to me should tend to the Sikhs.

23
00:02:31,449 --> 00:02:40,080
Another part of the scriptures described the Buddha finding a monk who had been abandoned by his fellows because of the sores oozing all over his body.

24
00:02:41,062 --> 00:02:50,733
His robes were sticking to him and again just imagine the stench and the sight of this man as he lay there abandoned and dying in agony.

25
00:02:52,496 --> 00:02:57,762
The Buddha boiled water and washed the monk with his own hands to clean off the pus.

26
00:02:58,669 --> 00:03:03,296
He similarly washed the soiled robes and attended the monk until these were dry.

27
00:03:04,519 --> 00:03:12,491
Once the monk had been comforted, the Buddha talked to him of the Dharma, and as you can expect, the monk became fully liberated.

28
00:03:13,733 --> 00:03:22,787
In both of these stories, the Buddha modelled a steadiness of heart that allowed compassion to flow where most people would retreat in alarm and disgust.

29
00:03:24,032 --> 00:03:30,462
At other times, compassionate action could take the form of warding off an aggressor.

30
00:03:31,685 --> 00:03:36,372
Sharon Salzberg tells the story of being attacked while in a rickshaw in India.

31
00:03:37,272 --> 00:03:43,562
She was badly frightened when she told her teacher Munindra Ji about the incident.

32
00:03:43,883 --> 00:03:51,153
He replied, Oh Sharon, with all the goodwill in your heart, you should have taken your umbrella and whacked that man with it.

33
00:03:52,079 --> 00:03:54,944
Compassion does not mean passivity.

34
00:03:55,627 --> 00:03:59,816
We can oppose injustice vigorously so as to prevent suffering.

35
00:04:01,158 --> 00:04:08,215
At other times there may be no appropriate action, no way to prevent or minimise the suffering.

36
00:04:08,549 --> 00:04:16,725
In those cases, just to stay nearby and witness the suffering is our only option and is a very precious gift.

37
00:04:17,427 --> 00:04:29,831
Simply staying with a suffering person, refusing to abandon them though we can offer no practical help, gives them the best possible opportunity to let their suffering open the door to wisdom.

38
00:04:31,144 --> 00:04:40,418
If we can take to heart the first noble truth that there is suffering, this opens the door to the other truths which liberate us from suffering.

39
00:04:41,720 --> 00:04:55,600
Whether we are caring for a sick person, vigorously opposing injustice or witnessing some suffering we cannot prevent, we need to be able to resist the reactivity which comes up in the face of suffering.

40
00:04:56,726 --> 00:05:02,399
Such non-reactivity is learned every time we sit with difficulties during Vipassana.

41
00:05:02,903 --> 00:05:10,392
even a slight pain in the knee, the noise of machinery, someone fidgeting nearby, a worrisome thought.

42
00:05:11,353 --> 00:05:13,997
All these are forms of suffering.

43
00:05:14,017 --> 00:05:30,160
As we learn to bear with these types of disturbance in meditation and their myriad spin-off thoughts and anxieties, we are cultivating the skills we need to respond compassionately in the face of deeper suffering in our own lives and in others.

44
00:05:32,079 --> 00:05:35,947
True compassion has this non-reactivity as its basis.

45
00:05:37,812 --> 00:05:50,038
Even though we may be speeding around in an effort to cope with the reality, a compassionate hurry is motivated by care rather than alarm and is completely at ease with the situation.

46
00:05:52,127 --> 00:05:57,896
Barriers to compassion, as with all forms of dukkha, come back to reacting to our feelings.

47
00:05:59,077 --> 00:06:06,269
In the case of suffering, there will be an unpleasant feeling at the core and the automatic urge to get rid of this.

48
00:06:07,490 --> 00:06:17,004
In many real life situations, we won't have the level of calm concentration needed to recognize this very simple level of our being.

49
00:06:18,317 --> 00:06:26,831
We will be spinning such a complex story around the unpleasant feeling that we get hooked by the myriad emotions that the story generates.

50
00:06:28,153 --> 00:06:33,360
The stories we tell ourselves at times of distress emanate from the perceptions of self.

51
00:06:34,523 --> 00:06:40,232
The notion that there is a substantial entity lodged somewhere in our body and mind.

52
00:06:41,514 --> 00:06:45,759
This self is, or should be, in control of matters.

53
00:06:46,312 --> 00:06:50,903
Imagine you have a pet goldfish who swims quietly around in a tank in your living room.

54
00:06:51,824 --> 00:06:58,220
Today when you sprinkle some food into the tank, Goldie doesn't dart around after these nibbles as he usually does.

55
00:06:58,940 --> 00:07:01,487
He stays put at the bottom of the tank.

56
00:07:01,466 --> 00:07:10,437
Taking a closer look at him, you notice he's lost some of his lustrous colour and there are some whitish spots in amongst his scales.

57
00:07:11,237 --> 00:07:19,706
By this stage there will be unpleasant feelings stirring, causing your face to frown and perhaps stiffening much of your body in tension.

58
00:07:21,127 --> 00:07:26,793
What happens next will depend on your habitual tendencies in the face of a perceived threat.

59
00:07:27,475 --> 00:07:30,158
Let's say you're a leap into action type.

60
00:07:31,117 --> 00:07:34,701
A sense of yourself as powerful and resourceful will be established.

61
00:07:35,221 --> 00:07:37,865
A determination to save Goldie from peril.

62
00:07:38,906 --> 00:07:46,117
Although you have hardly given Goldie a thought for months beyond tossing a few grains of food into the tank from time to time.

63
00:07:46,937 --> 00:07:55,228
He's fast becoming your nearest and dearest and a sense of enmity is forming around those whiter spots on his scales.

64
00:07:55,970 --> 00:07:58,033
Your eyes narrow as you examine them.

65
00:07:58,694 --> 00:07:59,113
Aha!

66
00:07:59,855 --> 00:08:00,516
Fungus!

67
00:08:01,593 --> 00:08:10,742
Dear Goldie, attacked by rotten spores of horrid fungus, outrage and indignation, it's you and Goldie versus the microscopic world.

68
00:08:11,363 --> 00:08:18,911
Don't worry, Goldie, you whisper into the fishbowl before making a dash to the computer to search for solutions to goldfish spots.

69
00:08:19,812 --> 00:08:26,841
You pace about in consternation as it goes through its infuriating start-up routine.

70
00:08:26,821 --> 00:08:35,658
Everything's going to be fine, you call, banging the keys furiously to get white spots goldfish into the Google's search line.

71
00:08:36,301 --> 00:08:37,764
Mummy's looking after everything.

72
00:08:39,947 --> 00:08:46,280
What's happening is that compassion has got entangled with one of its near enemies, pity.

73
00:08:46,902 --> 00:08:50,505
Pity lets us feel superior to the suffering person.

74
00:08:51,186 --> 00:08:57,351
Goldie has been reduced to a pathetic entity that you must rescue and restore to health.

75
00:08:58,192 --> 00:09:04,679
There's a clear separation between me, the valiant saviour, and Goldie, the poor creature who needs me.

76
00:09:06,100 --> 00:09:13,028
In pity, we can also be suppressing our fears that exactly the same kind of suffering could be visited on me.

77
00:09:14,375 --> 00:09:19,922
Thus we can quietly despise a drug addict while outwardly sympathising with their plight.

78
00:09:21,244 --> 00:09:26,029
The experience of compassion, on the other hand, unites us with the suffering person.

79
00:09:27,152 --> 00:09:30,056
Our own heart trembles in resonance with their plight.

80
00:09:31,538 --> 00:09:34,160
Pity so easily masquerades as compassion.

81
00:09:34,822 --> 00:09:39,488
It doesn't help that pity is listed as a virtue in many Christian texts.

82
00:09:40,159 --> 00:09:45,485
But in the context of the Christian virtue, the word pity is being used to mean compassion.

83
00:09:46,826 --> 00:09:50,390
The difference between the two is that pity includes aversion.

84
00:09:51,732 --> 00:10:02,085
We have generated a sense of enmity around the unwelcome sight of those white spots, which in turn evokes a sense of self to combat this enemy.

85
00:10:03,206 --> 00:10:08,731
In our rush to rescue, everything that gets in our way is seen as the enemy.

86
00:10:08,965 --> 00:10:18,052
computer delays, an incoming phone call, the rest of our agenda for the day, the cat crying for her saucer of milk.

87
00:10:18,833 --> 00:10:24,960
These are all irritating demands on our time which is urgently needed for poor little Goldie.

88
00:10:26,240 --> 00:10:36,389
And when our trawl through the websites convinces us that most fungal problems result from unclean water, we ourselves become the enemy.

89
00:10:36,977 --> 00:10:41,365
We berate ourselves angrily, trying to remember the last time we changed the water.

90
00:10:42,265 --> 00:10:48,475
Later, as we scrub and scour the tank, Goldie, in his replacement bowl, can also become the enemy.

91
00:10:48,995 --> 00:10:52,301
That good-for-nothing fish putting me to all this trouble.

92
00:10:53,962 --> 00:11:01,855
While compassion has goodwill as its basis, pity adds a big dollop of aversion to the mix.

93
00:11:02,458 --> 00:11:14,716
It's very easy for compassion to slide stealthily into pity when we are caring for someone who is ill. With compassion we can see the sick person's strengths as well as their illness.

94
00:11:15,216 --> 00:11:19,604
We respect them fully and value their friendship despite their reduced state.

95
00:11:20,424 --> 00:11:29,057
When compassion slides into pity we sense ourselves as strong and resourceful, the other as needy and weak depending on us.

96
00:11:30,774 --> 00:11:38,371
Whenever there's a very clear dividing line between yourself and the person you're caring for, it's likely that pity is emerging.

97
00:11:39,618 --> 00:11:43,504
Like attachment, pity is a normal aspect of human relationships.

98
00:11:44,245 --> 00:11:47,910
It gives us energy and motivation to look after vulnerable people.

99
00:11:48,793 --> 00:11:51,015
But it's destructive in the long term.

100
00:11:51,957 --> 00:11:56,384
In subtle ways, we might even be preventing the other person from recovering.

101
00:11:57,386 --> 00:12:00,591
We fuss over them, trying to anticipate their every need.

102
00:12:01,212 --> 00:12:04,477
We sympathise profoundly with every complaint.

103
00:12:04,457 --> 00:12:09,523
We counsel against taking any risks, never mind what the doctor says.

104
00:12:09,802 --> 00:12:11,083
Doctors don't understand.

105
00:12:12,544 --> 00:12:16,168
All of this excessive caring drains our energy.

106
00:12:17,129 --> 00:12:22,674
In our low moment we resent the sick person and we see ourselves as the victim of their neediness.

107
00:12:23,716 --> 00:12:27,278
The aversion has now found a different outlet.

108
00:12:28,500 --> 00:12:33,924
Instead of the sickness being the enemy, the sick person turned into the enemy.

109
00:12:35,120 --> 00:12:40,645
To complicate matters, the sick person often reacts against the aversion underlying our pity.

110
00:12:41,346 --> 00:12:46,312
They resent being reduced to the role we are creating for them, the needy person.

111
00:12:47,453 --> 00:12:52,179
In their low moments they hate us for so clearly showing them their dependent status.

112
00:12:53,100 --> 00:12:56,224
Pity breeds resentment in both parties.

113
00:12:59,148 --> 00:13:04,653
When we see ourselves as the injured party, self-pity is a common reaction.

114
00:13:04,735 --> 00:13:09,989
Suppose we valiantly scrub out Goldie's tank and replace it with sparkling clean water.

115
00:13:10,711 --> 00:13:12,275
We do this daily for a week.

116
00:13:13,177 --> 00:13:15,124
But still Goldie isn't recovering.

117
00:13:15,826 --> 00:13:19,976
The spots are getting bigger and the food is still untouched.

118
00:13:19,956 --> 00:13:28,489
What started out as aversion to the spots now grows to encompass aversion to all the work I'm doing for no reward.

119
00:13:29,350 --> 00:13:31,013
It's all so unfair.

120
00:13:31,813 --> 00:13:33,515
It's not just Goldie who is injured.

121
00:13:33,856 --> 00:13:37,662
We've joined him and feel ourselves as the injured party.

122
00:13:38,721 --> 00:13:41,664
The only comfort is to sympathise with ourselves.

123
00:13:42,384 --> 00:13:58,178
We run through the story from our point of view and insist again and again that we're doing absolutely everything right and how unfair and awful it is that there's no good coming of our hard work.

124
00:13:58,198 --> 00:14:07,547
Sympathy feels pleasant and we cling to it, unwittingly prolonging and deepening the injured party role and nursing a victim mentality.

125
00:14:08,707 --> 00:14:13,371
We start telling all our friends about our plight, eliciting their sympathy.

126
00:14:14,092 --> 00:14:19,177
Goldie, who for months went quite unnoticed, becomes the centre of our lives.

127
00:14:20,958 --> 00:14:28,485
Instead of being the spring-into-action type, let's suppose your habit when faced with suffering is to crumple in grief.

128
00:14:29,447 --> 00:14:32,789
So when Goldie refuses his food, you stare at him in dismay.

129
00:14:33,610 --> 00:14:37,193
When you notice the white spots, your worst fears are confirmed.

130
00:14:38,014 --> 00:14:38,715
He's a goner.

131
00:14:40,011 --> 00:14:47,880
Your head hangs in misery until someone or something helps you snap out of it, leaving Goldie to his fate.

132
00:14:49,844 --> 00:14:56,991
While pity can spur us into action, grief takes the suffering so deeply inward that it paralyzes us.

133
00:14:58,014 --> 00:15:09,967
We mistake grief for compassion because we want the suffering to stop, but we overlook the role aversion is playing, distorting our perceptions, overstating the problem.

134
00:15:10,690 --> 00:15:17,618
I remember one time when I was sitting on a park bench watching a group of pigeons pecking at some food on the ground.

135
00:15:18,839 --> 00:15:22,403
I noticed that one of the pigeons had lost his toes on one foot.

136
00:15:23,725 --> 00:15:30,533
That leg ended in a bulbous stump and rather than walking he was hopping from place to place on the other foot.

137
00:15:31,894 --> 00:15:34,177
Oh no, I thought, how awful.

138
00:15:35,278 --> 00:15:38,402
Inwardly I was writhing and my face was wincing.

139
00:15:39,731 --> 00:15:42,515
I would have sworn that I was feeling the pigeon's pain.

140
00:15:43,376 --> 00:15:48,904
I had noticed that before, the belief that I could feel the pain of other beings when I saw their physical wounds.

141
00:15:49,865 --> 00:15:56,595
But I had never questioned this belief as my attention was always so fixed on thinking about the awfulness of their situation.

142
00:15:57,797 --> 00:16:03,445
However, this time I registered the belief and started to wonder about it.

143
00:16:04,488 --> 00:16:07,230
How could I possibly be feeling the pigeon's pain?

144
00:16:08,030 --> 00:16:09,173
It didn't make any sense.

145
00:16:10,274 --> 00:16:13,015
I don't have any special powers of that nature.

146
00:16:14,256 --> 00:16:19,883
I closed my eyes, took a few deep breaths and vowed to let mindfulness sort it out.

147
00:16:21,224 --> 00:16:24,567
It took a while and I went through a lot of fear and confusion.

148
00:16:25,548 --> 00:16:33,515
But after a while it was as if a veil lifted and I realised the pain was in my own body.

149
00:16:34,272 --> 00:16:38,619
It was simply an unpleasant tingling at the base of my spine.

150
00:16:39,840 --> 00:16:43,164
Once I could locate the pain, it became quite bearable.

151
00:16:44,407 --> 00:16:48,173
My mind stopped amplifying it and projecting it onto the pigeon.

152
00:16:49,754 --> 00:16:52,119
After a few moments, I hardly even noticed it.

153
00:16:53,059 --> 00:17:00,751
I opened my eyes again, and this time when I looked at the pigeon, I noticed how well the pigeon was coping with his lameness.

154
00:17:01,693 --> 00:17:04,567
how he was managing to hold his own and get at some food.

155
00:17:06,073 --> 00:17:11,738
I saw that he was actually quite plump and healthy looking.

156
00:17:12,223 --> 00:17:22,512
Within this more hopeful scenario, my spirits lifted and with this came a simple wish that he come to no harm on account of his injury.

157
00:17:23,453 --> 00:17:32,241
Instead of feeling awful about him, I felt respect for this plucky attitude and grateful that he had taught me a worthwhile lesson.

158
00:17:33,423 --> 00:17:40,829
Since then, I've never been quite so overcome when seeing a person or animal with a physical injury.

159
00:17:43,325 --> 00:17:48,753
When we are grief-stricken in the face of suffering, aversion is colouring the whole scene.

160
00:17:50,096 --> 00:17:56,567
We can only think in negative terms about the suffering person, about ourselves, about the future.

161
00:17:57,488 --> 00:18:02,936
We've taken one instance of suffering and magnified it out of all proportion.

162
00:18:04,064 --> 00:18:06,507
just as I was doing in the case of the pigeon.

163
00:18:07,268 --> 00:18:08,450
This paralyses us.

164
00:18:09,230 --> 00:18:17,761
We've become so bound up in suffering that we have no resources left to add anything positive to the situation, not even a good wish.

165
00:18:19,144 --> 00:18:24,911
A child stands by in mute misery as their sibling is punished by an enraged parent.

166
00:18:25,791 --> 00:18:31,859
We look away from our bereaved neighbour, feeling anguish on their behalf but not knowing what to say.

167
00:18:33,105 --> 00:18:38,031
When grief gets overwhelming, we can go into a state of shock and even denial.

168
00:18:38,071 --> 00:18:42,457
A friend told me of her meeting with her cardiologist.

169
00:18:43,198 --> 00:18:52,789
When he told her she would need open heart surgery, she looked around to see who he was talking to because she knew it couldn't possibly be her.

170
00:18:54,852 --> 00:18:55,353
C.S.

171
00:18:55,373 --> 00:18:56,193
Lewis book.

172
00:18:57,523 --> 00:19:05,055
A Grief Observed gives very honest and poignant account of the moment to moment experience of grief.

173
00:19:06,497 --> 00:19:11,644
The book was written from a journal he kept during the first weeks and months after the death of his wife.

174
00:19:12,625 --> 00:19:18,012
It opened with the statement, Nobody told me grief was so like fear.

175
00:19:19,276 --> 00:19:29,059
His perceptive inquiry showed him the fear underlying all the thoughts and emotions resulting from her loss.

176
00:19:29,079 --> 00:19:32,748
He needed company but dreaded when the spotlight was turned on him.

177
00:19:33,691 --> 00:19:36,778
Why can't they just talk to one another but not to me?

178
00:19:38,345 --> 00:19:49,796
His book gives many insights into the development of compassion and equanimity by means of his scrupulous and honest track through the suffering of bereavement.

179
00:19:51,678 --> 00:20:00,185
To develop compassion we need to learn to feel our fear without buying into the thoughts and perceptions it suggests to the mind.

180
00:20:01,207 --> 00:20:05,971
It can motive us to sit through knee aches and itchy noses when we remember this.

181
00:20:06,931 --> 00:20:20,017
As we learn to disentangle the knots of confusion that emerge in reaction to these, we are freeing our capacity for compassion in response to the inevitable sorrows of life.

182
00:20:20,037 --> 00:20:26,609
Grief, pity and overwhelm are examples of the near enemies of compassion.

183
00:20:27,771 --> 00:20:33,138
We sympathise with the suffering person and wish to relieve the suffering.

184
00:20:33,159 --> 00:20:38,144
But the very thought of suffering gives rise to these reactions.

185
00:20:40,166 --> 00:20:48,857
At the opposite extreme of reactivity we have cruelty which is the direct opposite or far enemy of compassion.

186
00:20:51,039 --> 00:20:57,188
Cruelty shows up in circumstances where we feel threatened and need to defend ourselves.

187
00:20:57,521 --> 00:21:01,086
Anger arises and energises us to overcome our enemy.

188
00:21:02,088 --> 00:21:07,395
But then the anger sticks around even in victory, compelling us to twist the knife.

189
00:21:08,518 --> 00:21:16,209
Cruelty prolongs the other's suffering and enjoys the power that enables us to do this.

190
00:21:16,229 --> 00:21:23,579
Cruelty can take the form of bullying, where the more vulnerable person is physically or emotionally abused by the bully.

191
00:21:24,184 --> 00:21:30,712
We regularly read of abuse of animals, children, the elderly and those with mental and physical handicap.

192
00:21:31,794 --> 00:21:44,910
A recent academic review reported that if a physician was seeing 20 elderly patients a day, then at least one of these was likely to have been abused in the previous year.

193
00:21:44,890 --> 00:22:02,868
A recent probe into abuse of mentally handicapped adults in a care home in Ireland showed patients being treated with quite casual cruelty, refusing their requests to be taken to the toilet, being made to sit in their own urine, being slapped when they made a disturbance.

194
00:22:04,191 --> 00:22:12,940
And a few years ago, the UK Secretary commented that cruelty had become the norm in some health and social care institutions.

195
00:22:14,287 --> 00:22:21,354
Lots of cruelty is not from willful glee in the suffering of others but because we neglect to examine what is happening.

196
00:22:22,935 --> 00:22:31,845
As a society we tolerate widespread abuse of animals in factory farming and when they are transported on long journeys for slaughter.

197
00:22:33,007 --> 00:22:43,837
Even as vegetarians how often do we think of the suffering of cow and calf separated from each other so that we can enjoy our dairy milk and cheese.

198
00:22:45,134 --> 00:22:50,762
If fish could cry out, would we still be fishing as a peaceful recreation?

199
00:22:53,747 --> 00:23:06,467
As against so many instances of cruelty in our society, there are also outstanding individuals and institutions that oppose cruelty and treat the vulnerable with care and respect.

200
00:23:07,869 --> 00:23:12,676
Many voluntary organisations look after animal welfare.

201
00:23:14,007 --> 00:23:23,741
There are hospitals and care homes which don't hit the headlines but do quiet, often heroic work to care for the sick and the handicapped.

202
00:23:23,761 --> 00:23:30,432
Web-based pressure groups get millions of signatories daily in an effort to prevent injustice.

203
00:23:31,713 --> 00:23:39,946
All such efforts bear witness to the innate human quality of compassion, the antidote to cruelty.

204
00:23:41,259 --> 00:23:48,568
Hopefully none of us seriously committed to the Dharma will be involved in overt brutality.

205
00:23:49,611 --> 00:23:51,854
But cruelty can show itself in subtle ways.

206
00:23:52,954 --> 00:23:56,019
Does a sarcastic remark slip out now and again?

207
00:23:57,099 --> 00:24:00,585
Do we indulge daydreams where the boss gets his just desserts?

208
00:24:02,086 --> 00:24:08,414
When someone we dislike is losing an argument, are we secretly gloating, cheering on the opponent?

209
00:24:09,863 --> 00:24:16,810
When caring for a vulnerable person is our tone of voice at times chosen to show how idiotic we think they are?

210
00:24:16,851 --> 00:24:23,738
Or do we take it out on ourselves, chiding ourselves savagely when things go wrong?

211
00:24:25,779 --> 00:24:32,968
Because most of us are conditioned to view cruelty as apparent, it's very hard for us to admit to cruelty.

212
00:24:34,078 --> 00:24:44,054
It helps to remember the Buddha's assertion that the basic problem is ignorance, not understanding the nature of suffering and how to bring it to an end.

213
00:24:44,855 --> 00:24:50,664
Because of this, we make all kinds of mistakes in trying to shield ourselves from pain.

214
00:24:52,126 --> 00:24:54,130
One of these mistakes is cruelty.

215
00:24:55,932 --> 00:25:04,962
After the fall of Nicolae Ceausescu in 1989, the media probe into conditions in many Romanian orphanages.

216
00:25:05,864 --> 00:25:14,413
I remember one image in particular, a little boy of about two, hitting his head repeatedly against the bars of his cot.

217
00:25:15,255 --> 00:25:25,567
His face was cut and bruised and someone was trying to restrain him, but the moment they let go of his head, he would bang it forcefully against the bars again.

218
00:25:26,340 --> 00:25:30,988
I think he gave us a graphic image for the innocent mistake at the basis of cruelty.

219
00:25:32,589 --> 00:25:38,538
As I see it, he senses the world as awful and naturally tries to find a way out.

220
00:25:39,380 --> 00:25:44,847
Because he can't change anything else in his environment, he turns on himself.

221
00:25:45,788 --> 00:25:49,294
Banging his head against the bars gives him a sense of control.

222
00:25:50,692 --> 00:25:56,542
The sense of control is gratifying, probably his only source of pleasure, so he keeps it up.

223
00:25:58,026 --> 00:26:01,050
This is self-inflicted cruelty.

224
00:26:01,893 --> 00:26:03,836
But the child is not inherently cruel.

225
00:26:04,538 --> 00:26:07,343
He just can't find any other way of asserting himself.

226
00:26:08,644 --> 00:26:12,732
Similarly, our moments of cruelty do not make us a cruel person.

227
00:26:14,114 --> 00:26:22,750
For that moment we take the only pleasure we can envisage in the situation, delight in prolonging suffering.

228
00:26:23,893 --> 00:26:27,019
When conditions change, we can be kind and caring.

229
00:26:28,803 --> 00:26:35,936
Because we tend to judge cruelty as apparent, we find ways of denying or justifying our subtle cruelties.

230
00:26:36,135 --> 00:26:45,372
For example, the phrase, there is no other way to deal with them, can quickly dismiss the person and cover over our harshness.

231
00:26:46,554 --> 00:26:52,525
That kind of blanket justification is what allows institutional abuse to flourish.

232
00:26:53,550 --> 00:26:57,259
A culture of brutality can grow around such simple slogans.

233
00:26:58,201 --> 00:27:02,369
Such thoughts harden our hearts against whoever we are dealing with.

234
00:27:03,712 --> 00:27:11,609
In the stress of the situation, we are denying their humanness and vulnerability, their need for understanding and love.

235
00:27:13,041 --> 00:27:18,528
When we are being cruel, we delight in the misery of the suffering person or animal.

236
00:27:19,388 --> 00:27:25,295
By contrast, pity and grief lock us into some identity with the suffering state.

237
00:27:26,536 --> 00:27:36,445
The challenge is to find a balance, to open our hearts to suffering without taking on the role of perpetrator, heroic saviour or victim.

238
00:27:39,910 --> 00:27:42,271
At times compassion flows naturally.

239
00:27:43,702 --> 00:27:50,388
But then the suffering touches a deep core within and we sense ourselves taking one of the reactionary roles.

240
00:27:52,070 --> 00:28:00,258
We're suddenly flooded with aversion or overcome with anxiety and can't find any way back to the easy flow of compassionate goodwill.

241
00:28:01,398 --> 00:28:12,528
We need to be patient with our repeated encounters with the near and far enemies and find ways of working alongside these rather than expect them to disappear.

242
00:28:14,212 --> 00:28:21,786
To cultivate compassion the classic phrase is, may you be free from suffering, but vary this if it helps.

243
00:28:22,626 --> 00:28:25,352
For example, may you have a peaceful death.

244
00:28:26,854 --> 00:28:27,875
May you not despair.

245
00:28:29,018 --> 00:28:31,362
May you not be troubled by little things.

246
00:28:32,506 --> 00:28:35,388
Use images if these work better than words.

247
00:28:35,950 --> 00:28:39,734
Some people like to visualize a healing light flowing into a person.

248
00:28:40,576 --> 00:28:45,060
Others like to imagine the healing as emanating from their own breath.

249
00:28:47,523 --> 00:28:50,267
Remember, it doesn't matter if you don't feel anything.

250
00:28:50,548 --> 00:28:54,311
What matters is the wish that suffering will stop.

251
00:28:55,404 --> 00:29:09,614
In formal meditation it's best to start with someone who you know is having a hard time and then go through all the various categories of people, not forgetting yourself and ending by radiating in all directions.

252
00:29:10,695 --> 00:29:16,047
It helps to take a few breaths so as to relax between each good wish.

253
00:29:17,596 --> 00:29:21,480
Directing compassion at the difficult person is often a challenge.

254
00:29:22,122 --> 00:29:31,675
Don't be surprised if the far enemy emerges and you find yourself thinking, well, they deserve it, and gloating gleefully at their plight.

255
00:29:32,936 --> 00:29:35,500
This is part of the purification process.

256
00:29:36,221 --> 00:29:46,876
Even if we don't behave in overtly cruel ways, the practice of compassion can show up our deep fears where cruel retaliation seems like our only defence.

257
00:29:48,967 --> 00:29:52,194
Glimpsing our underlying savagery can be quite dismaying.

258
00:29:53,377 --> 00:30:00,375
One teacher told me that the deeper we go in meditation, the more clearly we see that we have the seeds of all things within us.

259
00:30:01,278 --> 00:30:06,029
The child molester, the schoolyard bully, the rapist, the murderer.

260
00:30:06,009 --> 00:30:16,653
Our job is to recognise these urges, see them in the calm light of wisdom and decide not to follow them because they lead to suffering.

261
00:30:17,796 --> 00:30:26,314
Our usual reaction of self-judgment is a second arrow which deepens the suffering rather than relieves it.

262
00:30:28,031 --> 00:30:38,391
The more practice we get at letting go of the second arrow, the more easy it will be to feel the enticement towards cruelty and contemplate this calmly.

263
00:30:39,732 --> 00:30:41,435
Where do these urges come from?

264
00:30:41,476 --> 00:30:47,626
In my own experience, I sense cruelty as a refusal to forgive.

265
00:30:48,265 --> 00:30:53,471
Deliberately shutting my heart to myself or others gives me a self-righteous glow.

266
00:30:54,291 --> 00:30:59,897
But if I look carefully at that glow, there is a shadow side, the sneer of the tyrant.

267
00:31:01,318 --> 00:31:10,169
To give an example, I ordain when I come here to Satyapanya, but then go back into civvies when I am at home in Dublin.

268
00:31:12,211 --> 00:31:14,913
I also wear a wig to cover up my bald head.

269
00:31:16,582 --> 00:31:31,131
I haven't told many people in the family as many of the older generation were brought up in a strict form of Catholicism and I reckon they wouldn't be cheered up by the thought of having a Buddhist nun, even just part-time one, in the family.

270
00:31:33,067 --> 00:31:35,170
As you can guess, the inevitable happened.

271
00:31:35,911 --> 00:31:37,933
My aunt came to visit for a few days.

272
00:31:38,534 --> 00:31:41,178
I was in my room getting ready to go to bed.

273
00:31:41,778 --> 00:31:47,525
I had taken off the electrolarynx and the wig when I heard her knocking at my door.

274
00:31:48,405 --> 00:31:53,211
I couldn't tell her wait a moment because the electrolarynx was at the other side of the room.

275
00:31:54,252 --> 00:32:02,603
I just managed to grab the wig when I saw the door open and her head appearing around to ask whether she could take a sandwich.

276
00:32:04,877 --> 00:32:09,546
For a second she gaped at me in horror while I glared at her in fury.

277
00:32:10,208 --> 00:32:20,786
I was infuriated at the invasion of privacy, leaving my bald head suddenly exposed and my own powerlessness to say anything in protest.

278
00:32:20,806 --> 00:32:29,501
I barely managed a curt nod to indicate she could take all the blasted sandwiches she wanted so long as she got out of my room fast.

279
00:32:31,269 --> 00:32:45,414
Although I was very angry, mindfulness let me watch the process play itself out and after a while I was able to giggle at the humour of the situation and see that she had meant no harm.

280
00:32:46,593 --> 00:32:54,444
When I could manage to forgive, I felt the welcome relief of friendliness and the wish to meet with her and explain all.

281
00:32:55,626 --> 00:32:58,491
But then a deeper tangle showed itself.

282
00:32:58,511 --> 00:33:07,065
How to explain my attraction to ordaining as a Buddhist nun within what I anticipated as her abhorrence at the idea?

283
00:33:07,618 --> 00:33:16,498
In an instant friendliness was replaced with an image of myself fully wigged up, haughtily asking her not to enter my room until I answered the door.

284
00:33:17,881 --> 00:33:26,538
It would have been so easy to ignore the note of cruelty in this, painting it over with a thought like, that's what she deserves for being so rude.

285
00:33:27,582 --> 00:33:40,646
But because I could sense the glow of power as I clung to that haughty image, I recognised the underlying cruelty and had to admit that this wasn't exactly in keeping with my aspirations as a Buddhist nun.

286
00:33:43,731 --> 00:33:54,289
With that, the journey towards forgiveness resumed, and the following morning I was able to explain that I was now enrobing when I'd come to Sati Panya.

287
00:33:55,211 --> 00:34:03,286
The conversation went through a few ups and downs, but ended with her telling me of a sorrow she bears in regard to her own religious life.

288
00:34:04,448 --> 00:34:08,355
Thus we ended with a sense of mutual understanding and compassion.

289
00:34:09,735 --> 00:34:20,278
One great advantage of being able to recognise and work skilfully with our own urges towards cruelty is that we can start to understand and forgive cruelty in others.

290
00:34:21,141 --> 00:34:28,115
We can practice compassion even for tyrants whose cruelty has caused horrendous suffering in the world.

291
00:34:29,041 --> 00:34:37,554
No longer so horrified by our own feelings of cruelty, we can imagine their world and feelings and the feelings that drove them.

292
00:34:38,697 --> 00:34:43,143
We can take them to heart and wish that they find forgiveness for their deeds.

293
00:34:44,606 --> 00:34:50,536
Sometimes when we feel our own cruelty, the second arrow of self-judgment brings on anxiety.

294
00:34:51,418 --> 00:34:54,001
This is the flip side of cruelty, fear.

295
00:34:55,096 --> 00:34:57,119
Suppose a bully is taunting his victim.

296
00:34:57,860 --> 00:35:02,469
The glee comes from the thought, this is happening to you, not to me.

297
00:35:03,851 --> 00:35:06,916
But bullies can't maintain their superiority forever.

298
00:35:07,717 --> 00:35:13,487
Sooner or later, perhaps in sickness or in old age, they have to admit their vulnerability.

299
00:35:14,550 --> 00:35:19,297
Knowing what can happen to vulnerable people, they are petrified.

300
00:35:21,505 --> 00:35:27,996
Think of how much reassurance you would have to give that person before they would dare to trust you.

301
00:35:29,579 --> 00:35:41,539
That is the amount of reassurance we need to give ourselves when we catch a glimpse of our underlying urges towards cruelty and shrivel back in fear of ourselves.

302
00:35:42,869 --> 00:35:55,693
If we can keep reassuring our inner bully that they will only meet with kindness and forgiveness, then any urge towards cruelty can be transformed to the response of compassion.

303
00:35:57,056 --> 00:36:03,307
Before finishing this section on working with cruelty, let me say a word about self-judgment.

304
00:36:04,688 --> 00:36:12,398
We have to be careful just to note this impartially rather than reacting and thinking we shouldn't be so judgmental.

305
00:36:13,378 --> 00:36:20,007
When we can calm down and see things impartially, such judgment can even become an ally.

306
00:36:21,230 --> 00:36:33,666
Guy Armstrong, a renowned Vipassana teacher, tells how he found it impossible to forgive someone for their behavior until he saw the element of cruelty in his anger.

307
00:36:34,945 --> 00:36:41,371
His self-image revolted against the notion of himself as cruel and this persuaded him to forgive the person.

308
00:36:43,034 --> 00:36:47,699
So in this case, his conditioning to censure cruelty served him well.

309
00:36:49,360 --> 00:36:57,190
Within the light of wisdom, all our emotional habits can be transformed so that they can help us along the path.

310
00:36:59,987 --> 00:37:08,550
At other times when you bring a suffering person to mind, you might find yourself being pulled towards pity.

311
00:37:09,512 --> 00:37:13,202
For example, getting lost in plans or worries about how you could help.

312
00:37:14,304 --> 00:37:17,052
Or you could find yourself getting overcome by grief.

313
00:37:18,144 --> 00:37:30,264
Recently, a meditator described how he would become saturated by a kind of horrified anxiety when he was practicing compassion for the refugees trying to find their way into Europe.

314
00:37:31,507 --> 00:37:35,132
Or your mind may just go blank and refuse to engage.

315
00:37:36,034 --> 00:37:37,777
This is another example of grief.

316
00:37:38,798 --> 00:37:42,144
In this case, grief has led to overwhelm.

317
00:37:43,289 --> 00:37:47,735
These are all instances of the near enemy of compassion.

318
00:37:49,137 --> 00:38:01,675
Try to simply acknowledge and continue knowing that the emergence of the enemies near or far just indicates that we are ploughing new depths in our heart.

319
00:38:01,695 --> 00:38:06,503
So we don't have to be discouraged by them or start judging ourselves because of them.

320
00:38:07,284 --> 00:38:10,309
Smile at them if possible and soldier on.

321
00:38:12,297 --> 00:38:18,125
We're not interested in how we feel, remember, but in the wish that suffering be alleviated.

322
00:38:19,306 --> 00:38:23,052
So we can put these feelings to one side and focus on the good wish.

323
00:38:24,934 --> 00:38:31,182
Similarly, for any of the hindrances, acknowledge and then re-engage with the compassion practice.

324
00:38:32,480 --> 00:38:39,085
If self-judgment, pity or any emotions become overwhelming, experiment with self-compassion.

325
00:38:39,967 --> 00:38:41,748
May I be free from self-judgment.

326
00:38:42,389 --> 00:38:43,769
May I be free from pity.

327
00:38:44,610 --> 00:38:46,012
May I be free from grief.

328
00:38:47,293 --> 00:38:48,454
Or add in some meta.

329
00:38:49,094 --> 00:38:53,679
May I be happy and confident and free from self-judgment.

330
00:38:55,320 --> 00:38:55,882
And so on.

331
00:38:57,083 --> 00:39:00,545
Radiating compassion is quite a challenging practice.

332
00:39:01,623 --> 00:39:07,472
In ordinary life, our hearts have so many clever tricks to stop us from acknowledging suffering.

333
00:39:08,574 --> 00:39:10,797
In compassion practice, we do the opposite.

334
00:39:11,358 --> 00:39:18,068
We ask ourselves to think about the suffering of our friends, our benefactors and all other categories of people.

335
00:39:19,309 --> 00:39:28,744
We need to remind ourselves that in compassion, as for all Brahma-Vihara practice, we always try to make things as easy as possible for ourselves.

336
00:39:29,719 --> 00:39:37,672
Look for the route of least resistance in the heavenly direction and be prepared to experiment.

337
00:39:39,074 --> 00:39:46,844
For example, it often helps to switch back to Metta regularly and think of the person in happier circumstances.

338
00:39:48,047 --> 00:39:51,811
Or try putting a hand on your heart to steady yourself.

339
00:39:52,871 --> 00:40:09,690
I often prefer to work on compassion while walking rather than sitting and when the going gets tough it often helps to look around, not at people but at surfaces and furniture and to touch surfaces as I pass them by.

340
00:40:10,731 --> 00:40:15,436
This practice, remember, deliberately brings suffering to mind.

341
00:40:15,416 --> 00:40:17,318
So it can bring up deep fear.

342
00:40:18,320 --> 00:40:25,989
Looking at surfaces and touching them helps reassure me of the basic goodness of the world.

343
00:40:28,512 --> 00:40:37,762
If the emotions become overpowering, then I take a Vipassana break, acknowledging the emotion without any attempt to generate goodwill.

344
00:40:40,190 --> 00:40:44,637
Finally, let's look for a moment at how we practice compassion in daily life.

345
00:40:45,860 --> 00:40:50,768
Any effort to alleviate suffering is also a practice of compassion.

346
00:40:52,693 --> 00:41:04,594
For example, feeding the birds, looking after a sick friend, contributing to good causes, campaigning for human or animal rights, safeguarding the environment.

347
00:41:06,514 --> 00:41:11,780
If we have hurt someone, we could apologise and see if there's any way to make reparation.

348
00:41:13,101 --> 00:41:20,286
To practice self-compassion, we could make time for an activity we enjoy like swimming, yoga or music.

349
00:41:21,608 --> 00:41:25,112
The near and far enemies will also surface in daily life.

350
00:41:26,713 --> 00:41:36,302
The attempt to engage with vulnerable people may show us how callously we feel towards them, how easily we get exasperated by their limitations.

351
00:41:36,907 --> 00:41:40,331
As in meditation, acknowledge and continue.

352
00:41:41,594 --> 00:41:46,101
Remember, the opening of the heart naturally brings up these defense mechanisms.

353
00:41:47,182 --> 00:41:53,952
The experience of callousness could indeed be welcomed as a sign we are moving beyond our comfort zone.

354
00:41:56,143 --> 00:42:00,552
At the other extreme we might be fussing anxiously about them.

355
00:42:00,572 --> 00:42:08,248
Here we need to restrain ourselves and if we feel overwhelmed by the situation we need to extend compassion inwardly.

356
00:42:09,489 --> 00:42:16,684
This may mean simply wishing ourselves well or we could reinforce the wish with a caring gesture.

357
00:42:18,300 --> 00:42:26,353
May we find ways to comfort and encourage ourselves through every obstacle as we develop true compassion.

